‘The sea is ours’: Bolivia surrounded by land hopes court will reopen path to Pacific
Sailors patrol a disguised naval base in La Paz.
Public buildings have raised a blue flag.
Naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are moulded with the motto: “The sea is ours rightfully.
It is our duty to return.”
Throughout mainland Bolivia, the memory of the coast lost to Chile in a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still fresh, as is the longing to navigate the Pacific Ocean again.
Those hopes may now be the highest in decades, while Bolivia awaits a decision by an international court on October 1 after five years of hearings.
“Bolivia has momentum, a spirit of unity and calm and of course expects a positive outcome,” said Roberto Calsadia, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the international court's ruling on the big screens everywhere in the country, hoping that the Hague tribunal will rule in favor of Bolivia's lawsuit that, after decades of volatile talks, Chile is obliged to negotiate to grant it a sovereign outlet to the sea of Bolivia.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president who faces a controversial re-election battle next year, also depends heavily on Monday's verdict.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," he said.
But some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to rule in Bolivia’s favor and that it will not change much even to rule in their favor.
The Dutch-based UN body has no power to allocate territory to Chile and said it will not decide on the outcome of possible talks.
That the international court’s verdict comes just six months after the final arguments indicate that the case “was not complicated,” said Paz Zarate, an international law expert from Chile.
And the past four years may have set back the cause of Bolivia instead of improving it.
"The current Bolivian administration has used the problem of access to the sea for its own purposes," Zarate said.
Morales’ bellicose rhetoric undermined Chile’s remaining goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to talk at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to hold discussions after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Velce, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, dismissed the idea that the court's decision is unusually swift.
Monday will bring Bolivia "an incredible opportunity to open an era of good relations with Chile" and an opportunity to "put an end to 139 years of disagreement with mutual benefit," he said.
Kalsadia also denied that Morales, still one of Latin America's most popular presidents, used the sea problem as a political backing.
“Bolivia will never relinquish its right to access the Pacific Ocean,” he said.
“The decision is an opportunity to see that we have to overcome the past.”
