John Edward: linguistic skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding exam scores, which is only amplified by individual and group success in sport, art, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 students everywhere in Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further and higher education, the career they have chosen and their place as global citizens.
As an educational center that can design and implement tailored school curricula, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and desired as an elective in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it will make him arrogant.
If you speak to him in his own language, it will strike him in the soul.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s recent exam results, we can observe that languages outperform all other subjects with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a higher score of "5+".
Data collected from 74 SCIS schools showed that 72 percent of students scored higher "5+" in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those learning German, 69 percent of those learning French, and 63 percent of those learning Spanish also scored "5".
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly acquire in the future.
Languages are now, as an elective, seen at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics) in independent school curricula as well as elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the Commission on Employment and Skills of the OK noted that 17 percent of the reasons employers cited for failure to fill jobs were due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more mandatory in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more jobs demanding languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future having such a lifelong skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically give the polyglot an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults from OK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to talk, and French was the only language spoken by more than ten percent, or 15 percent of people.
Therefore, investing in language teaching is now important for today’s children.
Having more languages, especially those of developing economies, will equip children with a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will differ according to the languages it teaches.
Several schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important in OK when looking into the future by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
No matter what your child’s interests are, there will always be numerous languages to choose from in independent schools, with professors who are specialists in the field.
Scottish Independent Schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future brings.
At present, it cannot be denied, in the global business environment, that languages will continue to be vital for the future of the country, so this must be replicated in schools.
In fact, modern languages really should be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
"Il faut bien le faire" (it must be done).
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
