North Korea says there is “no chance” of disarming unilaterally without trust
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the extended sanctions deepened mistrust of the United States and that there was no chance the country would unilaterally give up nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body’s annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” last year, such as stopping nuclear missile tests, dismantling nuclear test facilities and committing itself against the proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"We don't see an appropriate response from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our national security, and under such conditions there is no way to unilaterally disarm first.”
Although Ri reiterated North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to nuclear disarmament that would gradually reward North Korea for the steps taken, his statement seemed significant because it did not reject unilateral, nuclear disarmament without discussion, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri alluded to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit of the incumbent U.S. president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work for “nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula,” while Trump guaranteed North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused to back down on tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'nuclear disarmament first and foremost' and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal by coercion, and even opposes the 'declaration to end the war,'" Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a futile dream of people who don’t know us.
But the problem is that the existing sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the US leader highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months, adding: “If the other side in this nuclear disarmament issue was South Korea instead of the United States, nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula would not have ended at such a dead end.”
Still, Ri’s tone of speech was significantly different from last year when he told the U.N. General Assembly that targeting North Korean missiles on the U.S. mainland was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened “total destruction” of North Korea, has praised Kim for his courage to take steps for disarmament, but said much work remains to be done and that sanctions must remain until North Korea’s nuclear disarmament.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for it, saying “whether it takes two years, three years or five months doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia believe the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The Security Council sanctions must continue fully and without exception until complete, definitive nuclear disarmament is confirmed.”
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions on North Korea since 2006 to curb funding for Pyongyang's nuclear weapons and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the U.N. General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but the last time did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July with a statement that progress had been made, but was denied by North Korea just hours later due to "gangster demands".
North Korea has pledged to meet with Moon this month to disarm a missile facility and a nuclear complex if the United States takes "appropriate measures".
He said Kim had told him that the “appropriate measures” he was seeking were the security guarantees Trump had given in Singapore, as well as moves toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Take Courses to Get Enough Vacation
A new course at Harvard University this year aims to teach all graduates more sleep in order to combat the growing macho culture of learning by staying awake all night with the help of caffeine.
One researcher found that students at the world’s leading university often know nothing when it comes to basic self-care.
Charles Chaizler, a professor of dream medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Women’s Hospital, is designing what he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a speech on the impact of insufficient sleep on learning.
“At the end of the lecture, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me this now, in the last year?’
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was offered for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help in academic and athletic performance, and improve overall well-being.
Paul Barrera, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of health services at the university, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students had a serious sleep deficiency during the week.
The course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a dorm where students press on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, and how insufficient sleep affects athletic performance and the importance of bedtime routines.
In another section, participants learn about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks and strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to rethink their daily routine.
“We know that it will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know about the health effects when you choose to smoke a cigarette.”
A culture of pride in “working all night” still exists, he said, and moreover, modern technology and increasing pressure on students mean that lack of sleep is a growing problem.
To have enough sleep, of good quality, should be the “secret weapon” of the student in the fight against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid obesity, because lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, which makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond Saw, a 19-year-old California student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chaizler design the course after attending one of his classes last year, in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to take action for a course throughout the student city.
He hopes the next step is to ask all postgraduates to complete a similar program before joining a competitive institution.
Professor Chaizler recommended that students think about setting an alarm about when to go to bed, as well as about when to wake up and be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which shifts the circadian rhythm, leading to problems with falling asleep.
