Almanach: The Inventor of the Geiger Counter
And now one page of our almanac "On Sunday morning": September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and we are counting ... the day when the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, a discovery that led to the creation of the device known as the Geiger counter.
Since then, the Geiger counter has become a mainstay of science and popular culture, as in the 1950 film The Bell of Colorado, starring the seemingly inconclusive, cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: "What is it now?"
Rogers: “It’s a geiger counter, which is used to locate radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put the headphones on, you can hear the effects of the atoms emitting radioactivity into the minerals."
Evans: "Say, it's probably jumping now!"
Hans Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
But the discovery that bears his name still exists.
A new cancer vaccine could teach the immune system to “see” alienated cells
A new cancer vaccine could teach the immune system to “see” alienated cells and kill them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize alienated cells as part of treatment
The method involves the extraction of immune cells from the patient and their alteration in the laboratory
You can “see” the protein common in many types of cancer and then be returned to the body
The trial vaccine gives promising results in patients with multiple cancers.
In a woman treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize foreign cells, ovarian cancer disappeared in 18 months.
The method involves extracting immune cells from the patient, altering them in the laboratory so that they can “see” a common protein in many cancers called HER2, and then returning them to the body.
Professor Jay Berzofsky, of the American National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results indicate that we have a vaccine that promises a lot.”
HER2 “stimulates the growth of several cancers,” including breast cancer, ovarian cancer, lung cancer, and colorectal cancer, Professor Berzofsky explained.
A similar approach by extracting immune cells from patients and “learning” how to target cancer cells works in the treatment of a particular type of leukemia.
