Special cameramen will be placed in key locations around the property to monitor bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile research using handheld detectors.
Expert analyses of the sounds from all recordings will determine the frequency depending on the species of bats.
Then a map of the habitats will be drawn to create a detailed picture of their behavior in the landscape.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of life are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain forests for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and Britain has declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects the beds and the loss of habitat.
Windmills and lights also pose a risk, as do fly adhesive tapes and some chemical treatments for building materials, as well as domestic cat attacks.
Bats aren't actually blind.
However, due to their habits of hunting at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo-location technique to find insects and obstacles in the flight path.
NTS, which takes care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 acres of land in the state, takes bats very seriously.
There are ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, inspections of beds, and sometimes rescues.
The organization even established the first and only bat reserve in Scotland on the Treve Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten species that live in Scotland.
