New information on the red tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinelas, Manati and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Commission, conditions of uneven flowering of algae have been observed in the Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier districts, indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide, a consequence of the flowering of red algae, stretches about 130 miles off the coast from North Pinelas County to South Lee County.
Parts of the red tide can also be seen about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but the number is still lower compared to last week.
A red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Over the past week, the following concentrations have been observed: average concentrations in or on the coast of Pinelas County, low to high concentrations on the coast of Hillsborough County, common to high concentrations in or on the coast of Sarasota County, common to medium concentrations in or near Charlotte County, common to high concentrations.
In Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties, cases of respiratory irritation continue to occur.
No cases of respiratory irritation have been reported in Northwest Florida over the past week.
